&gt; Here we go with envelopes versus messages.  The presentation of the
&gt; envelope should be under control of the user agent program.  If we
&gt; believe that the across-the-net syntax is independent of the user
&gt; interface, then we need strong statements that users should never see
&gt; raw envelope data -- some agent should be turning it into
&gt; human-comprenensible form.  If that means reversing the ends, adding a
&gt; rooting character, or whatever, then so be it.
&gt; 
&gt; If we believe that there will never be real user interfaces, then we had
&gt; best redesign the net format to be person-friendly.

This is the philosophy taken by X.400, that the user interface can be
whatever the implementor likes.  I don't buy that philosophy.

The problem is that there needs to be a standard way for a human to
write down a mailing address.  People will exchange mailing addresses
via inband means (within the bodies of their mail) and by other media
(business cards, pieces of paper, viewgraphs, etc.)  People also will
want to exchange mailing lists.  Everything gets very confused if there
is no standard syntax for doing this.

The following is an actual signature found in message.  It is an
example of the sort of thing that evolves when there are no standards
(or too many standards.) Let's not adopt positions that encourge this
sort of thing!

	Mark

--- enclosure follows

